    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-08-07T18:11:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-08-07T18:11:00-05:00" n="52"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d52">
                <head>52. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Burma</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d52fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 690B.9331/8–556. Secret; Priority. Repeated to London, Bangkok, and
                            <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-08-07T19:11:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 7, 1956—7:11 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>142. Rangoon’s 157 sent London 9 Bangkok 13.<note n="2" xml:id="d52fn2">Telegram
                        157, August 5, reported that <persName corresp="#p_SJC1"
                            >Satterthwaite</persName> had discussed the Burma-China border situation
                        with <persName corresp="#p_KNU1">U Kyaw Nyein</persName>, who inquired about
                        the the U.S. position. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>) A few days earlier,
                        press reports had revealed the presence of Chinese Communist troops in
                        certain disputed areas near the border.</note> Department studying
                    ramifications Burmese territorial claims along Chinese border in preparation
                    possibility US some time future may be asked support <gloss target="#t_GUB1"
                        >GUB</gloss> in international forum.</p>
                <p>In meantime you may wish assure <gloss target="#t_GUB1">GUB</gloss> continued US
                    interest and sympathy towards finding solution this problem.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d52fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJC1">Satterthwaite</persName> reported in telegram
                        218 from Rangoon, August 16, that he had so assured Prime Minister
                            <persName>U Ba Swe</persName>. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.,</hi>
                        690B.9331/8–1156)</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>: Present thinking in view uncertain course
                    Chinese Communist action Burma border dispute and problem Chinese Communist
                    representation <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>, would not wish encourage
                        <gloss target="#t_GUB1">GUB</gloss> place matter before <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> if possibility exists Peiping’s active
                    participation <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> forum or enhancement Chinese
                    Communist prestige. However, agree little likelihood <gloss target="#t_GUB1"
                        >GUB</gloss> will seek <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> assistance unless
                    Chinese Communists slam door on diplomatic negotiations. End <gloss
                        target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
